text:
Most Flutter mobile apps start clean.
Then features grow. Deadlines shrink.
And suddenly… refactoring feels dangerous.
The problem isn’t Flutter.
It’s architecture.

In this series, I’ll explain the SOLID principles and how to apply them in real-world Flutter development to build scalable, testable, and maintainable apps.

O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP).
Software entities should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
🚨 The Flutter Reality
Most widget trees violate OCP without us realizing it.
Let’s say we build a payment screen:

Widget buildPaymentButton(PaymentMethod method) {
 if (method == PaymentMethod.card) {
 return CardPaymentButton();
 } else if (method == PaymentMethod.paypal) {
 return PaypalPaymentButton();
 } else if (method == PaymentMethod.applePay) {
 return ApplePayButton();
 }
}
Looks harmless.
But every time we add a new payment method:
We modify this function
We risk breaking existing logic
We increase merge conflicts
We violate OCP
This code is not closed for modification.
🧨 Real-Life Scenario
Imagine your product team adds:
Google Pay
Crypto payments
Buy Now Pay Later
Each new feature forces you to reopen and modify stable code.
That’s technical debt accumulating silently.
✅ Applying Open/Closed Properly in Flutter
Instead of conditionals, use abstraction + polymorphism.
1️⃣ Define a Contract
abstract class PaymentButton {
 Widget build();
}

2️⃣ Implement Concrete Variants
class CardPaymentButton implements PaymentButton {
 @override
 Widget build() => CardPaymentWidget();
}

class PaypalPaymentButton implements PaymentButton {
 @override
 Widget build() => PaypalPaymentWidget();
}

3️⃣ Use Dependency Injection
class PaymentScreen extends StatelessWidget {
 final PaymentButton paymentButton;

 const PaymentScreen({required this.paymentButton});

 @override
 Widget build(BuildContext context) {
 return paymentButton.build();
 }
}

Now:
Adding GooglePay? → Create a new class.
No existing code changes.
No risk to stable logic.
Fully OCP compliant.
🎯 Why This Matters in Large Flutter Apps
In production apps:
Features evolve constantly.
Multiple teams work in parallel.
Releases happen weekly (or daily).
OCP helps you:
✔ Avoid touching stable code
 ✔ Reduce regression bugs
 ✔ Improve scalability
 ✔ Make feature flags easier
 ✔ Enable plugin-like architectures
This is especially powerful when combined with:
Clean Architecture
Strategy pattern

OCP is not about removing if statements.
It’s about identifying axes of change.
Ask yourself:
“What is most likely to grow in this feature?”
If the answer is:
Payment methods
Notification types
User roles
API providers
Themes
Then design for extension — not modification.
That’s architecture thinking. 😊
